00:01:16,500 --> 00:01:18,500
Section 1

19
00:01:18,500 --> 00:01:34,000
I'm joined today by Matthew Piscitelli who has worked as an archaeologist, a university professor, and an explorer for the National Geographic Society.

20
00:01:34,000 --> 00:01:37,500
Welcome Matthew and thank you for being here.

21
00:01:37,500 --> 00:01:43,000
Now my first question for you is this, why should people care about archaeology?

22
00:01:43,000 --> 00:01:46,500
Why should we care about some stones and bones?

23
00:01:46,500 --> 00:01:55,000
I think it's important to study objects from the past, from ancient civilizations, because of the old cliché that we learn about the future by studying the past.

24
00:01:55,000 --> 00:02:01,000
The past is who we are. We learn more about where we come from and it helps us learn more about our identity today.

25
00:02:01,000 --> 00:02:06,000
We need to study those ancient civilizations so we can help prepare for the future.

26
00:02:06,000 --> 00:02:10,000
And archaeology is also important because it inspires curiosity.

27
00:02:10,000 --> 00:02:15,000
People feel a connection to the past when I say, you know, you're walking in the footsteps of ancient people.

28
00:02:15,000 --> 00:02:19,000
Or, this is what it was like to live 5,000 years ago.

29
00:02:19,000 --> 00:02:21,000
I think there's something very interesting about that.

30
00:02:21,000 --> 00:02:29,000
So it's important that we as archaeologists not simply do our excavations, write a report, and then file that away where nobody will read about it.

31
00:02:29,000 --> 00:02:33,000
We need to communicate what we do and the importance of what we do.

32
00:02:33,000 --> 00:02:37,000
We need to ask ourselves, why does what you propose to do really matter?

33
00:02:37,000 --> 00:02:44,000
Who's going to care beyond a few specialists in your field? Are you asking questions that can inform us about humanity, about culture?

34
00:02:44,000 --> 00:02:47,000
Those are all great questions.

35
00:02:47,000 --> 00:02:56,000
Now, I think it's fair to say that when most people think about archaeology, they think about uncovering objects from cultures like ancient Greece, Rome, and Egypt.

36
00:02:56,000 --> 00:03:03,000
Why do you think that is? What is it about societies like these that inspires us so much?

37
00:03:03,000 --> 00:03:10,000
So there are a lot of famous sites in the world, like Stonehenge and the Pyramids of Giza, that people are always excited to learn about.

38
00:03:10,000 --> 00:03:15,000
And there's something charismatic about them. They have been around for thousands of years.

39
00:03:15,000 --> 00:03:22,000
People, not just us today as consumers of media or tourists, but there have been tourists for hundreds of years.

40
00:03:22,000 --> 00:03:25,000
So people have constantly been interested in these sites.

41
00:03:25,000 --> 00:03:29,000
And I think it's from the charisma, the wonder, the awe of these sites.

42
00:03:29,000 --> 00:03:32,000
It's something about archaeology that makes us wonder.

43
00:03:32,000 --> 00:03:39,000
What was it like to live in the past? What was it like to build the pyramids or to build Stonehenge?

44
00:03:39,000 --> 00:03:43,000
What did they mean? Those voices aren't here to talk to us today.

45
00:03:43,000 --> 00:03:48,000
Are there any archaeological sites or ancient cultures you think people should know more about?

46
00:03:48,000 --> 00:03:54,000
When we look at all of the work that our National Geographic explorers are doing all over the world,

47
00:03:54,000 --> 00:04:00,000
we come to realize that the world is a very ancient place, and there are a lot of civilizations out there to be discovered.

48
00:04:00,000 --> 00:04:04,000
Now in some of those places, like in Egypt, there's a long history of study.

49
00:04:04,000 --> 00:04:09,000
Some other places are more like the Wild West, and that we don't know as much.

50
00:04:09,000 --> 00:04:16,000
For example, in Peru we know Machu Picchu. We know some sites along the north coast of Peru, which are very famous.

51
00:04:16,000 --> 00:04:30,000
[silence]

